item.title: North Korea Blows Up Liaison Office With South
item.description: Ahead of the destruction of the jointly run facility, which closed earlier this year, Pyongyang had warned of military action in statements aimed at the South.

item.title: Global Coronavirus Infections Pass Eight Million
item.description: More than eight million people world-wide have been infected by the coronavirus, according to Johns Hopkins University data, and nearly 437,000 have died. In the U.S., at least 2.11 million have been infected.

item.title: Doctors Without Borders Ends Work at Afghan Maternity Ward After Attack
item.description: Doctors Without Borders is ceasing operations at a maternity ward in Kabul that was attacked last month, in a sign of how insecurity continues to plague Afghanistan despite U.S. efforts to reduce violence.

item.title: Protests in U.K. Spark New Scrutiny of British Empire
item.description: The killing in police custody of George Floyd and subsequent protests in the U.K. have prompted an unexpected outcome in Britain: an impassioned debate about the British Empire.

item.title: New Covid-19 Outbreak in China Rattles Beijing
item.description: Travel plans evaporated, parents kept children home and anxiety returned as China’s capital came to terms with a new outbreak of the novel coronavirus after many in the city had started to relax the habits adopted during the height of the pandemic.

item.title: Former Marine Found Guilty in Russia of Espionage, Sentenced to 16 Years
item.description: Paul Whelan was found guilty of espionage and sentenced to 16 years in prison in a case that has drawn condemnation from the U.S. and threatens to further worsen relations between Moscow and Washington.
